 Beijing's equivalent of the Bastille for the next eighteen years. Informed by vivid firsthand accounts of the relations between the Dalai Lama, the Nationalist Chinese government, and the People's Republic of China, this absorbing chronicle illuminates one of the world's most tragic and dangerous ethnic conflicts at the same time that it relates the fascinating details of a stormy life spent in the quest for a new Tibet.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  a20th century tibetan history.  aasian history.  aautobiography.  abapa phuntsok wangyal.  achinese communist party.  acommunism.  adalai lama.  agovernment and governing.  aguerrilla uprising.  ahistory.  amao zedong.  anationalist chinese government.  aphuntsok wangyal goranangpa.  aphuntsok wangyal.  aphunwang.  apolitical ideology.  apolitics.  aqincheng.  arepublic of china.  arevolution.  arevolutionary.  asino tibetan relations.  asolitary confinement.  atibet.  atibetan communist party.  atibetan politician.1 aSherap, Dawei, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSiebenschuh, William R, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094030740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940307423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520940307/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles